<TITLE> Brazil opposition demands resignations after crash </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRASILIA, July 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Brazilian opposition leaders demanded on Wednesday the resignation of Defense Minister Waldir Pires and aviation authorities after the country's worst ever air crash killed as many as 200 people. A jetliner skidded off a wet landing strip after dark on Tuesday at Sao Paulo's Congonhas airport, slammed into a cargo terminal and exploded into flames. The main runway the plane tried to land on was recently paved but not yet grooved to help drain rain water. "Reopening a runway that was not ready is tantamount to murder, they should go to prison," said Onyx Lorenzoni, head of Democratas opposition party in the lower house of Congress. The heads of the airport authority Infraero, the aviation authority ANAC and Pires should resign, he told Reuters. Air traffic in Brazil is managed by the Air Force and has been in disarray since another serious air crash killed 154 people last September. The latest accident could be a catalyst for growing opposition to President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, analysts said. "His image will be stained, there should be some impact on his popularity, although judging by the ratings so far it won't be too serious," said Carlos Lopes, a political consultant in Brasilia. Lula's approval ratings have remained largely intact despite an ongoing aviation crisis that also caused repeated delays and cancellations at airports. "People are frightened (to fly)," said Antonio Carlos Pannunzio, head of the opposition Brazilian Social Democracy Party, or PSDB, in the lower house of Congress. "(Pires) has nothing left to do in office, if he ever did anything," he added. A PSDB legislator died in the accident on Tuesd
